## Base Conversion and Representation

Numbers can be written in any base. Base 10 is what we're used to, but computers use base 2 (binary), base 16 (hexadecimal), and number theorists sometimes use other bases.

### Converting to Another Base

```scheme
(nt/base-convert 42 2)
```

[VISUAL: Print the list `(1 0 1 0 1 0)` representing 42 in binary: 101010₂.]

<!-- BUILD: run; print the list of digits -->

42 in base 10 is 101010 in base 2.

```scheme
(nt/base-convert 255 16)
```

[VISUAL: Print `(15 15)` representing FF₁₆.]

<!-- BUILD: run; print the list of digits (15 is F in hex) -->

```scheme
(nt/base-convert 100 5)
```

[VISUAL: Print `(4 0 0)` representing 400₅.]

<!-- BUILD: run; print the list of digits -->

In base 5, 100₁₀ = 4×5² = 400₅.

### Continued Fractions

A *continued fraction* is a way to represent a number (often irrational) as a sequence of integer quotients:

x = a₀ + 1/(a₁ + 1/(a₂ + ...))

For rationals, the continued fraction is finite.

```scheme
(nt/continued-fraction 3.14159 10)
```

[VISUAL: Print a list of the first 10 coefficients of π's continued fraction.]

<!-- BUILD: run; print the list -->

The continued fraction of a rational number:

```scheme
(nt/continued-fraction (/ 22 7) 10)
```

[VISUAL: Print `(3 7)` (22/7 = 3 + 1/7).]

<!-- BUILD: run; print the list -->

Continued fractions give the best rational approximations to a number.

